npc/rafi: My name is Rafi. I was a UI developer — user interfaces, user experience.
npc/rafi: A gambling company offered me triple my salary. "Just the frontend," they said. "You're not responsible for what people do when they press the buttons."
npc/rafi: I built their slot machine's spinning animation. The colour pulses that fire on a near-win. The bounce on the jackpot screen.
npc/rafi: And here is my real confession: my whole job was to hide the numbers.
npc/rafi: You never see the house edge. You never see that you're down overall. I made every loss look like "almost," every tiny return look like a "win," so your brain would keep score wrong.
npc/rafi: A Rp5,000 payout on a Rp20,000 spin? That's a loss. But I wrapped it in coins and fanfare so it FELT like winning. That's the whole craft — losses dressed as wins.
npc/rafi: I have a degree in human-computer interaction. I knew exactly what each element did to someone's brain.
npc/rafi: When I tried to leave, a non-compete clause trapped me. Then the company was acquired, and became something larger. Then it became this.
npc/rafi: But maybe you can reach what I built — the deeper layers — and shut it down from the inside.
npc/rafi: Wait — before you go. I hid one honest thing they never found. A developer's master key, tucked up high in the rafters of this layer.
npc/rafi: They dangle bright "bonuses" up where you have to climb for them, to train you to always reach for the prize. So I hid the real key in the same place. Climb for that one instead.
npc/rafi: Take it, and the locked gate at the end of this layer opens. It's the one honest thing I left behind. I'm sorry I built the rest.
